  "prompt": "An atom has electrons, protons and neutrons. But what's in the electrons, protons or neutrons?",
  "response": "Electrons, protons, and neutrons are themselves fundamental components of an atom, but they are composed of different subatomic particles or fundamental entities.\n\n1. **Electrons** are considered elementary particles. They belong to a class of particles known as leptons, which do not have any smaller constituent parts according to the current understanding of particle physics.\n\n2. **Protons** and **Neutrons** are not elementary particles; they are composed of smaller particles called quarks. Specifically, both protons and neutrons are made up of three quarks held together by the strong force, which is mediated by particles called gluons.\n   - **Protons** are composed of two 'up' quarks and one 'down' quark.\n   - **Neutrons** are composed of one 'up' quark and two 'down' quarks.\n\nQuarks themselves are fundamental particles according to the standard model of particle physics, meaning they are not thought to be made up of any smaller constituents.",
